        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The date is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-6967.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Charles Lyell, 2 November 1869</ref>, and by the date of CD’s visit to the <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_8646.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">British Museum</ref> (see n. 6, below).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">The missing sheet of the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-6967.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Charles Lyell, 2 November 1869</ref>, has not been found.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-6967.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Charles Lyell, 2 November 1869</ref> and nn. 4 and 5.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">For CD’s allusion to the endurance of continents in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6014.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Origin</hi></ref>, see the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-6967.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Charles Lyell, 2 November 1869</ref> and n. 8. In <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1571.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Coral reefs</hi></ref>, CD argued that reefs formed as the immense area (or continent) on which they were built subsided over a long period of time; see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1571.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Coral reefs</hi></ref>, pp. 142–4, and <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_3575.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Herbert 2005</ref>, pp. 242–3.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5">Lyell may have discussed subaerial denudation in Scotland in the missing portion of his letter of 2 November 1869.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f6">CD visited the <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_8646.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">British Museum</ref> on 3 November 1869; there is a dated note made on his visit in DAR 85: A71.</note>
        </div>        
            
